# UCSC Team Creates Wildfire Prep Games

If youâ€™ve lived in California for a long time, you know that wildfires are very common here. Just this year, a massive fire ravaged the Los Angeles area. According to [the EPA](https://www.epa.gov/climate-indicators/climate-change-indicators-wildfires), wildfires are a natural part of ecosystems, but they can still be very dangerous. Additionally, human activity has made wildfires more frequent and dangerous than what would normally occur in nature. For example, climate change has led to hotter and drier weather, which are perfect conditions for wildfires. Wildfires can destroy homes and cause deaths, and the smoke can harm air quality, affecting the health of people far from the source.

A group of researchers at UCSC recently released a collection of video games designed to teach people about how to prepare for a wildfire. According to their [website](https://ucsc-wildfire-games.itch.io/), the primary project is a game titled â€œWildfire Minigames Collectionâ€. This collection includes three games. In one game, named â€œFirewise Residentsâ€, the player must help residents prepare for a wildfire. Another, named â€œFind Your Thingsâ€, involves collecting emergency supplies. The final one is a two-player game called â€œFireSafe Friendsâ€ about improving oneâ€™s home to be more fire resistant. The page, named â€œWildfire UCSCâ€, also features a number of other games and prototypes, all on the same theme of wildfire preparation. The developers also performed a number of studies to determine how effective the games are educationally, and have published their findings.

Development was a collaborative effort, involving a number of workshops and support from experts. The project was funded by the National Science Foundation, as part of a program called Smart and Connected Communities. According to one of the [developersâ€™ posts](https://ucsc-wildfire-games.itch.io/wildfire-minigames-collection/devlog/981870/launching-a-game-for-impact-the-challenges-without-a-marketing-budget), this provided enough funding for the game itself, but not for marketing, which made it hard to get word out about the game. However, a number of news sources have covered the project, so it has not entirely gone unnoticed. 

The games created by this project can help to educate people about wildfire preparation, which could keep them safer and prevent deaths. Knowing what supplies to have in the event of an evacuation and how to protect your home is very important for people who live in areas threatened by wildfires. However, the gamesâ€™ ability to reach people who might benefit from them are limited by the lack of promotion. This presents a conundrum because the game needs to be free so that everyone can access it, but the project still needs money for purposes such as this.

Games can be a useful tool for education. They can make learning information more interesting and memorable. They can also help train people to do things, by acting them out in a simulation. This project combines both approaches, allowing the player to act out safe practices while also learning about why those practices are important. This approach could be very useful in keeping communities informed about not just wildfires, but many other urgent topics. While games are generally meant to be fun, projects like this show how that fun can be leveraged for purposes other than entertainment, keeping the audience engaged and informed.
